  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "CHAPTER 2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jud 2:1-10. An Angel Sent to Rebuke the People at Bochim.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1-3. an angel … came from Gilgal to Bochim—We are inclined to think, from the authoritative tone of his language, that he was the Angel of the Covenant (Ex 23:20; Jos 5:14); the same who appeared in human form and announced himself captain of the Lord's host. His coming from Gilgal had a peculiar significance, for there the Israelites made a solemn dedication of themselves to God on their entrance into the promised land [Jos 4:1-9]; and the memory of that religious engagement, which the angel's arrival from Gilgal awakened, gave emphatic force to his rebuke of their apostasy.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Bochim—\"the weepers,\" was a name bestowed evidently in allusion to this incident or the place, which was at or near Shiloh.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I said, I will never break my covenant with you … but ye have not obeyed my voice—The burden of the angel's remonstrance was that God would inviolably keep His promise; but they, by their flagrant and repeated breaches of their covenant with Him, had forfeited all claim to the stipulated benefits. Having disobeyed the will of God by voluntarily courting the society of idolaters and placing themselves in the way of temptation, He left them to suffer the punishment of their misdeeds.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
