    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I said",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " I now declare to you my resolve. It was this that made the people weep. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thorns in your sides",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is not a translation of the Hebrew text, which only has \"for sides,\" but a partial adaptation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the phrase is \"scourges in your sides and thorns in your eyes.\" Either the words for \"scourges in\" have fallen out of the text, or the word here rendered \"sides\" should be rendered, as some think, \"enemies.\" A snare. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 8:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note. Judges 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"And I also have said to you:\" these words point to the threat already expressed in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the event of their not fulfilling the command of God, which threat the Lord would now fulfil. From the passages mentioned, we may also explain the expression לצדּים לכם והיוּ, they shall be in your sides, i.e., thorns in your sides. לצדּים is an abbreviated expression for בּצדּיכם לצנינים in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so that there is no necessity for the conjecture that it stands for לצרים. The last clause of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is formed after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
